You could generally fix anything by googling and finding a solution posted on reddit, you could install various Adblockers, it was tolerable. Now we're slowly transferring to a new era of constant bugs, inability to do anything easily, constantly having to reinstall drivers, etc.

There was a period of time from the 90s until like 2013 when computers didn't work. There were constant unpredictable system errors, browsers randomly froze and crashed, blue screens of death, just constant headaches every day. Then there was a decade when things actually worked.

There is a 1:1 correlation of technological decline in terms of user experience and "cloud storage" being forced everywhere. I don't think anyone has ever actually wanted to upload his files on the cloud or to Google Drive or literally anything other than a physical hard drive.
"Kitsch" is another word that has run out of its usefulness long ago and is better left in the past.
